                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d563">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">838.51/3517: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Port-au-Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-23T16:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 23, 1937—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 5:21 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>164. President Vincent has received a telegram from Leger stating that in spite
                    of the firm offer of the Biens Privees they are now unable to proceed with the
                    loan. Leger states he has seen the President of the Council who promised to
                    discuss the matter with the Minister for Finance with a view to the immediate
                    conclusion of a loan and a commercial convention. Leger consequently has
                    requested Vincent to hold off further reduction of the coffee export tax for 8
                    days, but Vincent has, apparently, telegraphed Leger that the situation here is
                    grave and that Paris negotiations must be hastened.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Mayer</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
